John Edward: Language Skills are Essential for Global Citizens
Independent schools in Scotland benefit from a curriculum of academic excellence, with this trend continued in 2018 with another set of exceptional exam results, reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community initiatives.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to achieve the best level of service for both students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for deepening their studies and access to universities, as well as for the career they have chosen and to take their place as global citizens.
Since this is an educational sector capable of conceiving and implementing a tailored school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and sought-after topic in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: “If we talk to a man in a language he understands, we can get into his mind.
If we talk to him in his own language, we can get into his heart.”
This quote reminds us well that we can’t just rely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
Based on the results of this year’s recent exams, we check that the languages are at the top of the table, with the highest rates of exploitation of independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages reached the maximum rating of A.
These data, collected from the 74 schools under the SCIS, show that 72% of students obtained the maximum score of A in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that Scottish independent schools are favoring foreign languages as vital skills that will undoubtedly serve children and young people in the future.
Languages, as an option, are now addressed in the same way as STEM themes (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculum of independent schools and more.
A UK Employment and Skills Commission survey in 2014 found that among the reasons for employers’ difficulty filling vacancies, 17% were related to a lack of linguistic skills.
Knowing other languages is therefore increasingly an imperative to prepare the young generation for their future careers.
With more potential employment opportunities requiring knowledge of languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of your chosen career, if you have learned a second language, you will have a tangible advantage in the future with an aptitude for life like this one.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically put a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to maintain a conversation, with French being the only language spoken by a two-digit ratio, 15%.
Therefore, investing now in language teaching is important for today’s children.
The multilingual skills, particularly those in developing countries, will give children the best chance of finding a relevant job.
In Scotland, each school is different in the languages it teaches.
Some of them will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach languages considered the most important to the UK for the 2020 horizon, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, there will always be a set of languages to choose from in independent schools, supported by specialist teaching staff in the area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a pedagogical environment that prepares children and gives them the skills necessary for success, whatever the future reserves them.
It is undeniable that today, in a globalised business environment, languages continue to be of fundamental importance for the future of the country, so it is necessary to reflect it in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to make this option available with diversity and excellence to young Scots.
We have to do it right.
