The method involves the extraction of immune cells from a patient and their alteration in the laboratory.
These cells, which can "see" a protein common to many cancers, are then re-injected into the body.
An experimental vaccine is producing promising results in patients with a number of cancers.
A woman treated with the vaccine, who teaches the immune system to recognize harmful cells, saw her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months.
The method involves the extraction of immune cells from a patient and their alteration in the laboratory so that they can "see" a protein common to many cancers, called HER2. These cells are then re-injected into the body.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our findings suggest that we have a very promising vaccine.”
HER2 "controls the growth of various types of cancers", including those of the breast, ovary, lungs and also colorectal, Professor Berzofsky explained.
A similar approach to removing immune cells from patients and “teaching them” to attack cancer cells worked in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
